Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all its own to such facilities: coloured walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
The architectural projects firm Arch.Design, of which numerous well-known buildings of Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the building Avriopoint to include a space for its mini-guard.
In the company work about 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and delineants to return soon to work after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a small schedule, kindergarten is one of the benefits Arch offers.Design your workers within the framework of your social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Design's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-guard of the company is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the Czech Republic State budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a provision of over 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to buy equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to maintain the mini-guardry with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the submission of the request for funding contributed to the Economy Rating company.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day long. The day-care centre currently houses children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since this is a "ministership", it can only accommodate up to five children at the same time, even though with shifts they turn more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guard programme are comparable to the regular pre-school programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach even English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from work.
Parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is located among the companies that sign that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of staff.
The home of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar shape to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones."
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the new use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and the omnipresent lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and texture drawn from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and order are observed carefully thought out.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the torsion of the forms continue to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the rails, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district in the number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, emerged from the remodeling of an 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
Reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design it by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in its plans of the project, ornaments arose for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Park Güell de Gaudí, in which other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows, began to call it "the box house."
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of St. Jorge appears, master of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilating ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to see his 40 - five - degree inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the construction rules of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although clearly in it the indicated data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it requested that it be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public side.
The arrangements never took place, rather on the contrary: only fifteen days after the request of the town hall, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floors was installed the owner himself.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, with six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connection of space.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way without any problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and more recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the door to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
The visits confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entrance to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16,50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
