More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed to track vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device has the approximate size of a box of matches, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of invading your privacy.
"We are all trying to tell ourselves that it is not a matter of spying, but of another means to reduce the possibility of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in the event of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to take him, he will simply throw him away.
"Even younger children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"Before, the parents trusted the mobiles enormously, but they could be deleted as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child carries some type of electronic device that can reveal its location."
"Now it's the phone."
"The use of follow-up devices is being extended, and will also seek out them, since their sale will certainly take place with great publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised pedophile attack.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can serve as help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a given period."
"If you suffer damage, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices have a tilt meter integrated, so if the person simply slips and remains still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," Čech says.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with mobile phones with navigation, in which only a special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a box of matches or smaller mobile phones.
