Czech youth get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer so, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause them to end up in medical care young drinkers under 15 years of age.
The children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who are involved in such cases in the hospital's pediatric admissions.
"Beber beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because they take a long time to get drunk."
"Now fashion is the strong alcoholic beverages," says Prevo, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán.
"When they get a bottle from their father in the hall, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and does not smell so much," he explains.
The spokesman for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová, also confirms this.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use spiritists who took home," Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikan, they are drinkers of thirteen and fourteen years of age who usually appear in hospitals.
Prior to Hořovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where the ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It began at the age of twelve, when she was brought with 3.5 of alcohol in blood, in addition to a mixture of ecstasy," says the department doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that her mother was not surprised that her daughter disappeared 48 hours," the boss was surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of increased alcohol consumption among young people.
The experts point out that, in the case of children, it cannot be spoken of as a dependency.
"Alcoholic means a person who has chronic alcohol dependence for several years, with all the phenomena associated with alcohol, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, rather it is due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokesman Jurinová, this year in the pediatric clinic of Motol, forty drunk children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, statistics show only those with severe poisoning and should remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the medical examination, go home to their parents or to the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply meet after school and drink a spirit, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that can be mentioned: Witch Day, End of Year and end of school course.
"In such circumstances, they drink by bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"On the day of the witches I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at once," adds Pelikan.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injection of a serum with glucose and nutrients that are missing from the body.
"This is much better, because after the agitated night, they get up well and they don't hurt anything."
"Only when they are confused about where they are", says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose good humor at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The transfer into an ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients costs about ten thousand kroner.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when I tell the children directly on the visit how much it has cost their drunkenness and that they would have to spend all summer on a job for young people to earn enough to pay for that night," Pelikan adds.
The health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually returns people the treatment expenses, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
