A longer index finger than annular indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than annular are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It could depend on the testosterone level, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger may be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Therefore, the finger could help to determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this characteristic is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the shorter right-hand Indian finger than the annular finger.
They had the same chances of suffering from prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men with ages below 60%, the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined during the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the foetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer can be "shown completely".
