Support for democracy continues to increase in Latin America, as well as support for private enterprises.
Crime causes more concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a country more influential than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinbarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it allows for monitoring of changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related issues were highlighted in the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the relatively animated mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent per annum since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a low of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but significantly more than 25 per cent in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34 per cent stated that they trusted in the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher in relation to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis is likely that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty is only marginally increasing in 2009 and has been further reduced to 32 per cent this year.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see figure 5).
About 31 per cent say that either they or close relatives have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
Around 58 per cent agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared to 47 per cent last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same (and 80% support private companies), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by polled in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
