Cockell wasn't part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates replacing one element with another in biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one by another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"Arsenic, however, is different enough to make it not work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, by the way, calls biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
Researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, to which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
