Can civicism draw a bridge to unite divisions?
After a notable campaign for invective and negativity, a bit of civicism has been unleashed this week in Washington.
Is it a presage of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But for what they all say, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting of the President's Deficit Committee on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to state that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, each one seeking to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting of Tuesday and the subsequent evaluations of Tuesday by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and very deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the past two years.
Whether they are taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two parties are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened humor in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
The elections awaken partisan passions, which then go extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing meeting, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment subsidies to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible discussion on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement begins.
"After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
No matter how conscious Republican leaders are of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut state spending and cancel the new health law.
These lines of support are already clearly reflected in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in certain taxes and retirement age, and the cut-off of expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been tasked with one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the issue of the deficit into the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been fighting to get close to that figure.
The increased resistance is among the staff elected in the panel, suggesting that there are at least at present few bases or desire for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama about budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch with attention the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he's losing will probably change course and look for compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partidism and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find common points on the issues that still divide them.
