Sport and law fraud
Assholes like those of Alonso and Ramos before Ajax demonstrate ingenious but unwilling to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly hit by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether or not such behaviour is anti-sports and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team was already clearly winning), the two players deliberately lost time in removing missing paths to provoke the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid will end up as leader of its group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next game of the liguilla, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee has sanctioned with two parties the team coach, José Mourinho, and with different amounts of money to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather a frequent one in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case reported is due to the fact that it has been played by a team from the Real Madrid entity (who, in his hymn, boasts nobility and honor, and who has sometimes been fined their players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated history of his hystrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether such behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions commit legal fraud; for they are, in fact, actions respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question arises as to the type of damage to the sports spirit.
One of the goods that includes the sport spirit is the physical integrity of the opposite players, an aspect that with these actions was not jeopardized, i.e., there was no violent play.
Another of these items to which the clean game refers is to prevent the team of the violators from taking unfair advantage of the other team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not suit what we normally characterize as trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not made in hiding to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely its action tried to be the most evident in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders derive from the deliberate offences examined.
It seems necessary to note here that the rival is not placed in a disadvantageous position and no benefit is obtained from the same party, since obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the team can be eliminated at the first of the changes, and in addition with this performance players perform a penalty game and pass to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor to take full advantage of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of fraud of law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without drawing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I believe it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the directive was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
