I change rules to get visa
Persons should attend Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will be changed.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer a payment will be necessary to complete the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another payment to get the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with a request (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for trader and investor's visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but only come to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their marks.
Because biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the 26 dollars extra service fee.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
