The athlete, who stands out in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and thai box, goes up to the tatamis and rings of the world in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts like kung-fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria," said Zemmal, who has been living in the metropolis since 2008 to advance at the professional level.
"In my case, I seek combat everywhere because, for those who do not enjoy the game on the ground that involves mixed martial arts, there are few competitions in North America."
The athlete, who works as a security officer and as a UPS employee, has recently given bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Amateur Championship of the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA), held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I have won in the categories of kickboxing full contact and thai box," he explained.
"I am currently preparing to participate in the World Cup of San Shu in China."
"They will invite the sportsmen who have finished among the first four positions in the world's last championship in each category."
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto."
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished in eighth place."
"In 2007, in China, I finished the tournament in fifth place, but I reached third place in Toronto in 2009," he added.
"The interesting thing is that I've been making progress in every competition."
"At this point, I'll be the first this time or next year!"
The "san shou" or "sand" is a discipline originating in China in which it is allowed to strike with the fists and feet, as well as to throw the opponents to the ground.
The clashes are originally held on a platform and, less often, in a ring.
The most famous boxer in this type of combat is the American of Vietnamese origin Cung Le, widely recognized in the martial arts world.
Although Nacer Zemmal should only hold a competition in his career, he will definitely attend the great "King of Sanda" Kung-fu Super Bowl tournament.
"This competition is China's most notorious and prestigious," explains the friendly boy.
"It is like the equivalent of Lumpinee Stadium (the largest stadium in Thailand). "
"It's been an amazing experience."
Zemmal has won his first fight, in the semifinals of his category (80 kg), but lost in the final.
"He who has earned me is a real professional," he says.
"There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"The semifinal winners face the end of their category."
"Then the champions of each category face to crown a single champion, the king of the kung-fu."
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has granted direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the centre of this avalanche of more than one hundred contracts there is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a tender before the most important contract, the management of the project, in an amount of 295 million.
The consortium, called Energy Gerance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec's decision to entrust the private sector with its responsibility to manage this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Energy Gerance consortium obtained the lucrative contract without prior public tendering.
For the Quebec Party, resorting to business consortia poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and raise prices.
"This is a new method of collusion and of eliminating competition."
"I mean, people, instead of secretly doing it, now they do it openly," said Quebec MP Sylvain Simard yesterday in a press conference.
Earlier, in the morning, Mr Simard raised the matter in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can be benefited in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, strongly denying that there was a collision with this contract.
"I'm starting to get tired," he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted "honestly" and "with no rigor."
He pointed out that "the minimum" would be that the QP apologized.
The formula of consortia is a common practice throughout the world.
Normally, it is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a competitive bid for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already begun and will last until 2012.
In any case, the contract has been awarded without competition; it has been negotiated.
Moreover, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the standard in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the consortium formula in the technical advisory sector is being investigated in the Government.
A quick look at Quebec's commercial registry allows identifying more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, that is, Dessau.
With regard to the Energy Gerance consortium, Minister Normandeau pointed out that "the territory of the James Bay responds to a particular labor dynamics and Hydro-Québec responds specifically to it since the 1970s".
The great head of the Eastmain project, Real Laporte, of the Baie James Energy Corporation (SEBJ), has given an explanation that has highlighted the fact that the project management contract has been granted directly.
"If you respond to a bid and there are few participants, your prices will be higher."
"You have two options: you can get in touch with the players in the sector and tell them: we will negotiate a satisfactory agreement with a good price."
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of people," said Mr Laporte.
The contract awarded to the Energy Gerance consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After the verification, Le Devoir has identified 109 technical advisory contracts granted between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has obtained 22 contracts, Génivar obtained 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its participation in Energy Gerance.
All contracts were negotiated.
A total of $449,783,344, including the maintenance energy contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has suggested that the four companies forming the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "good known to the Liberal Party of Quebec".
Ms Normandeau has dropped that the QP is also linked to these companies, which "finance it", before specifying that it is rather about their leaders.
Responsible consumption barometer. Green label does not inspire confidence
More ecological, but deeply skeptical.
The consumer is hardly trusted in the actors of sustainable development, as well as in fair trade marks and ecological certificates to guide their elections.
According to the Barometer of responsible consumption, whose first results were published yesterday, the situation is even worse. The consumer is immersed in a media universe where they pulsate messages defending a more responsible consumption, but regrets the lack of reliable information and considers that it even slows down its commitment.
Even if the consumption of so-called "socially responsible" products has increased in 2010, the Quebec people seem to give very little credit to those who are trying to sell them.
Two thirds of them say, in fact, that they do not trust in the environmental commitment of the companies or environmental advertising of the companies, they reveal the measurement tool developed by the Sherbrooke University's Responsible Consumption Observatory.
Another conclusion: half of the consumers question the reliability of the official certificates that carry the products called fair, as well as the credibility of the products and brands that carry labels indicating that they are "ecorresponsible", says the Barometer.
Similarly, only 14.6 per cent of the Quebecers take the speeches of politicians seriously on this issue.
In any event, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this sector of consumption, currently supported by about one third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, gaps and the questionable nature of information make 46% of consumers desist from this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the highest price of these products.
In addition, one third of Quebecers say they are also distrusting the alleged returns of the ecological products or services they are trying to sell to them.
On the other hand, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their convictions.
61% have given priority to shopping in the shops in their neighborhood and has preferred to buy food grown in their region, says the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible (the responsible consumption index has reached 64 points over a hundred this year), the Homo consumus of Quebec loves to occupy the King's post of recycling that tries to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of the fauna.
However, according to the Barometer, this social awareness seems to be from doors (from their car) outside: in 2010, only 28% of the Quebecers indicated that they have used public transport or shared cars to defend their ecological principles.
In addition, 39.1% of the participants in this comprehensive behavioural survey, which has just completed its first edition, support the use of the bicycle and walking.
