The unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3 per cent on continental territory (9.7 per cent taking into account overseas departments), as indicated by the seasonally adjusted data (CVEs) published on Thursday by Insee.
The number of unemployed remains at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
Data from the second quarter have been confirmed, 9.3 per cent of the working population on continental territory and 9.7% with the DOMs.
In one year, the unemployment rate has recorded an increase of 0.1 points.
In general, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter, but want to work, whether or not they are available in the two weeks to work and look for employment or not.
The situation of young people in the labour market has continued to worsen, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2 per cent in continental France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year), 25% including the DOMs.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15-24 were unemployed in the ILO sense.
On the other hand, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among older people, up to 6.4% in continental France (+0.2 points over three months and over one year), i.e., 482,000 people over 50, which amounts to 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only unemployed persons aged between 25 and 49 have been unemployed, with 8.3% in continental France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
Insee has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, following a controversy over its calculation methods.
Eurostat, the European Union statistics agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October, after 0.9% in September.
