Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is exclusively made up of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not just because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who engage in occultism not only rely on what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that was sending the U.S. Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as it was published on Newsweek the previous week.
So why have they caused such a stir in the revelations of these files?
On the one hand, they only say what any cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since the Second World War and since the Heads of States can call on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just appear that we don't know it by hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of publicly repeating it violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of US diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "wisdoms".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, in Orwell's time, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction carried out, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the power eye.
But when it is shown, as now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be held that can no longer preserve its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be unveiled); it is also true that any knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put in the network any confidential information, since it would be like publishing it in a street sign.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential conversations cannot be expected on the telephone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has moved on a plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the time being, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novelism, but I imagine that government agents who move discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: at the end of the day, the spying attempt at Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances as a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a cable telegraph (telephonic).
The video tapes (analogues) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backwards, discovering all the secrets of mounting, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to advance or back from chapter to chapter, i.e., to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that communication politics and techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
Previously, the press was trying to understand what was secretly planned at the embassies.
It is currently the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's hats on its financing pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether rapidly unblocked financing promises (called fast start or early start) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to providing EUR 7.2 billion in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was a significant result and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society wanted all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which places it on the right track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has taken as its reference in 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years ' expenditure or to the total level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), while attempting to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the sharing of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro lent is equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more effective technologies), it is necessary to present a euro which will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated ... As a whole, only the cost of the loan to the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of a rate of interest) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros making 91.5% loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million); consult the EU document to see it in its own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that so often uses the loan.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when most of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France has a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending just EUR 36.1 million, it can give the impression that it spends "new and additional" 420 million, as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term detail in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the vast machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its method of calculation for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could make the discussions on the stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Moriset, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published on Wednesday by Générations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in the Oise and Paris supermarkets between July and September the foods that usually consume a child of about ten years in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as the golosins, were examined in the laboratories for chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances capable of acting as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although virtually all cases do not exceed the legal limits for each of the chemicals individually, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to potentially carcinogenic pollutants and/or PE is worrying," says the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a weather for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green jews of Kenya, including food, in which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian fillet, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were adhered to with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 detected chemical residues and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk generated by these "contaminant cocktails" for the consumer "probably underestimates", says the study.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
